Recursion is a technique where a method calls itself to solve a problem by breaking it into smaller sub-problems. It keeps calling itself until it reaches a base case (a condition where it stops), and then it combines the results while returning back.
Recursion simplifies problems like financial forecasting because growth over time is naturally repetitive — each year's value depends on the previous year's value. Instead of writing a loop to multiply repeatedly, recursion expresses this dependency directly: FV(n) = FV(n-1) × (1 + growthRate), which mirrors how compound growth actually works in real life.